'''Isaac de Leon''', who lived at [[Ocaña, Spain|Ocaña]], in [[Toledo, Spain]], was one of the last rabbis of [[Crown of Castile|Castile]]. He was a native of [[Kingdom of León|Leon]], and a pupil of [[Isaac Campanton]], and, like [[Moses de Leon]], a [[kabbalist]] and a believer in [[miracle]]s. [[Joseph Caro]] and others honored him with the title of "the great teacher." He was more than seventy years of age at his death, which occurred some years before the [[Alhambra decree|expulsion of the Jews from Spain]]; he was mourned by many pupils. The work ascribed to him, ''Megillat Ester,'' an answer to [[Nahmanides]]' criticism of [[Maimonides]]' ''Sefer ha-Miẓwot,'' has been proved by [[Chaim Joseph David Azulai|Azulai]] to belong to Isaac Leon ibn Zur, a later writer.

