{{Infobox saint |name=Saint Qardagh |image= |imagesize= |caption= |alt= |birth_date= |birth_place= [[Persia]] |death_date= 4th century |death_place= [[Arbil]], [[Adiabene]] |feast_day=Friday of the 14th week after the [[Pentecost]] |venerated_in= [[Chaldean Catholic Church]], [[Assyrian Church of the East]], [[Syro-Malabar Church]] |titles= |beatified date= |beatified place= |beatified_by= |canonized_date= |canonized_place= |canonized_by= |attributes= |major_shrine= Church of Mar Qardagh, [[Arbil]], [[Iraq]] }}
'''Mar Qardagh''' ({{lang-syc|ܡܪܝ ܩܪܕܐܓ}}), was a [[Sassanid]] prince who was [[Christian martyrs|martyred]] for converting to Christianity.<ref name="Walker2006">{{cite book|author=Joel Walker|title=The Legend of Mar Qardagh: Narrative and Christian Heroism in Late Antique Iraq|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H2UoQttQcy0C|date=25 March 2006|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-93219-7}}</ref>
==Life== Qardagh was born to a noble family in the [[Sassanid Empire]] during the 4th century. When Qardagh was 25 years old, [[Shapur II]] visited his parents’ estate and was impressed with Qardagh’s handsome appearance and athleticism. Qardagh was appointed as a governor for a large region in northern [[Persia]], there he met [[Abdisho]] ({{lang|syc|ܥܒܕܝܫܘܥ}}) and converted to Christianity.<ref name=stpeter>[http://www.kaldu.org/EasternSaints/MarQardagh.html Mar Qardagh] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111129054301/http://www.kaldu.org/EasternSaints/MarQardagh.html |date=2011-11-29 }}, St. Peter The Apostle Catholic Diocese for Chaldeans.</ref>
Upon returning home Qardagh was rejected by his family and under pressure from the religious elite, Shapur sentenced him to be [[Stoning|stoned]]. Qardagh fled with a small army to the mountains where he was able to repel the Persians for months. One night [[Saint Stephen]] appeared to him and told him that it was better to give his life for his faith than to continue fighting. He surrendered to the king and it was his own father who threw the first stone.<ref name=stpeter/>
He was buried in [[Arbil]], [[Adiabene]] where a church holding his relics was later constructed.<ref name=stpeter/>
